\subsection{Method \code{run_iNMF()}}{
Perform multi-omics integration and sample clustering using
integrative non-negative matrix factorization from the IntNMF package.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_iNMF(
  Clusters = NULL,
  MaxIter = 200,
  StabilityCount = 20,
  MatrixInit = 30
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{Clusters}}{The number of sample clusters to be created. Can be a
single integer to calculate a single cluster assignment, or a range to
calculate multiple cluster assignments. In iNMF, the number of clusters
is the number of low dimensions or components created.}

\item{\code{MaxIter}}{Number of iterations. Default is 200.}

\item{\code{StabilityCount}}{Count for stability in the connectivity matrix.
Default is 20.}

\item{\code{MatrixInit}}{Number of initializations of random matrices. Default
is 30.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_LRAcluster"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_LRAcluster}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_LRAcluster()}}{
Perform multi-omics integration and sample clustering using
LRAcluster for R as done in the MOVICS package.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_LRAcluster(Clusters = NULL, Linkage = "ward.D")}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{Clusters}}{The Number of sample clusters to be created. Can be a
single integer to calculate a single cluster assignment, or a range to
calculate multiple cluster assignments.}

\item{\code{Linkage}}{Agglomeration method to be used for the hierarchical
clustering. Must be one of: \code{"ward.D"} (default), \code{"ward.D2"}, \code{"single"},
\code{"complete"}, \code{"average"}, \code{"mcquitty"}, \code{"median"} or \code{"centroid"}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_COCA"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_COCA}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_COCA()}}{
Perform multi-omics integration and sample clustering using cluster
of cluster analysis from the COCA package.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_COCA(
  DatasetClusters = NULL,
  maxClusters = 12,
  DatasetClusterMethod = "hclust",
  DatasetDistance = "euclidean",
  FullClusters = NULL,
  maxFullClusters = 12,
  FullHClustMethod = "average",
  FullClusterMethod = "kmeans",
  FullDistance = "euclidean"
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{DatasetClusters}}{Number of clusters per omics dataset. If a single
integer, all omics datasets get the same number of clusters. If a vector
with the same length as the number of omics datasets, each dataset can get
a different number of clusters. If NULL, the number of clusters per
dataset will be estimated using the silhouette method, and argument
\verb{"maxClusters} should be included.}

\item{\code{maxClusters}}{Maximum number of clusters per omics dataset if
\code{DatasetClusters} is NULL. If a single integer, all omics datasets have the
same maximum number of clusters considered. If a vector with the same
length as the number of omics datasets, each dataset has an individual
maximum number of clusters considered. Default is 12.}

\item{\code{DatasetClusterMethod}}{String indicating the method to cluster the
individual omics datasets. If single string, all omics datasets are
clustered with the same method. If vector of strings, each omics dataset
is clustered with an individual method. Must be one of: \code{"kmeans"},
\code{"hclust"} (default) or \code{"pam"}.}

\item{\code{DatasetDistance}}{Distance to be used in clustering of the
individual omics datasets. If single string, all omics datasets are
clustered with the same distance. If vector of strings, each omics
dataset is clustered with an individual distances. Must be one of:
\code{"euclidean"} (default, available for \code{"kmeans"}, \code{"hclust"} and \code{"pam"}),
\code{"manhattan"} (available for \code{"kmeans"}, \code{"hclust"} and \code{"pam"}),
\code{"gower"} (available for \code{"pam"}), \code{"maximum"} (available for \code{"kmeans"}
and \code{"hclust"}), \code{"canberra"} (available for \code{"kmeans"} and \code{"hclust"}),
\code{"binary"} (available for \code{"kmeans"} and \code{"hclust"}) or \code{"minkowski"}
(available for \code{"kmeans"} and \code{"hclust"}).}

\item{\code{FullClusters}}{Number of clusters after integration. Can be a single
integer to calculate a single cluster assignment, or a range to calculate
multiple cluster assignments. If NULL, the number of clusters will be
estimated using the silhouette method, and argument \code{"maxFullClusters"}
should be included.}

\item{\code{maxFullClusters}}{Maximum number of clusters if \code{FullClusters} is
NULL. Default is 12.}

\item{\code{FullHClustMethod}}{Agglomeration method to be used for the
hierarchical clustering of the integrated dataset. Must be one of:
\code{"ward.D"}, \code{"ward.D2"}, \code{"single"}, "complete"\verb{, }"average"\verb{(default),}"mcquitty"\verb{, }"median"\code{ or}"centroid"`.}

\item{\code{FullClusterMethod}}{String indicating the method to cluster the
integrated dataset. Must be one of: \code{"kmeans"} (default) or \code{"hclust"}.}

\item{\code{FullDistance}}{Distance to be used in clustering of the
integrated dataset. Must be one of: \code{"pearson"}, \code{"spearman"},
\code{"euclidean"} (default), \code{"manhattan"}, \code{"maximum"}, \code{"canberra"},
\code{"binary"} or \code{"minkowski"}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_MOFA"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_MOFA}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_MOFA()}}{
Perform multi-omics integration using multi-omics factor analysis
from the MOFA2 package.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_MOFA(
  PerformCluster = TRUE,
  Clusters = NULL,
  Factors = NULL,
  ScaleViews = FALSE,
  SpikeSlabFactors = FALSE,
  SpikeSlabWeights = TRUE,
  ARDFactors = FALSE,
  ARDWeights = TRUE,
  MaxIter = 1000,
  Convergence = "fast",
  StartELBO = 1,
  FreqELBO = 1,
  Stochastic = FALSE,
  SaveData = FALSE,
  Outfile = NULL
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{PerformCluster}}{Whether to perform k-means clustering on the sample
embeddings. Default is \code{TRUE}.}

\item{\code{Clusters}}{The number of sample clusters to be created. Can be a
single integer to calculate a single cluster assignment, or a range to
calculate multiple cluster assignments.}

\item{\code{Factors}}{Number of factors (components).}

\item{\code{ScaleViews}}{Whether to scale the different omics datasets to be
scaled to have the same unit variance. Default is \code{FALSE}.}

\item{\code{SpikeSlabFactors}}{Whether to use spike and slab sparsity on the
factors (components). Default is \code{FALSE}.}

\item{\code{SpikeSlabWeights}}{Whether to use spike and slab sparsity on the
features. Default is \code{TRUE}.}

\item{\code{ARDFactors}}{Whether to use ARD sparsity on the factors. Default is
\code{FALSE}.}

\item{\code{ARDWeights}}{Whether to use ARD sparsity on the weights. Default is
\code{TRUE}.}

\item{\code{MaxIter}}{Maximum number of iterations. Default is 1000.}

\item{\code{Convergence}}{String indicating the convergence criteria. Must be
one of: \code{"fast"} (default), \code{"medium"}, or \code{"slow"}.}

\item{\code{StartELBO}}{Integer indicating the first iteration to compute the
ELBO statistic. Default is 1.}

\item{\code{FreqELBO}}{Integer indicating the frequency of ELBO computations.
Default is 1.}

\item{\code{Stochastic}}{Whether to use stochastic inference. Default is \code{FALSE}.}

\item{\code{SaveData}}{Whether to save the trained MOFA model. Default is
\code{FALSE}.}

\item{\code{Outfile}}{File path to save the trained MOFA model.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_SNF"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_SNF}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_SNF()}}{
Perform multi-omics integration and sample clustering using
similarity network fusion from the SNFtool package.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_SNF(
  Distance = "euclidean squared",
  Clusters = NULL,
  Neighbors = 20,
  Sigma = 0.5,
  Iter = 10,
  SpecClusterType = 3
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{Distance}}{String indicating the distance used to calculate the
distance matrices for each omics dataset. If single string, distance
matrices are only calculated for that distance. If a vector of strings,
distance matrices are calculated for all distances, and clustering will
be performed for all distances. Can be: \code{"euclidean squared"} (default
in SNF), \code{"euclidean"}, \code{"manhattan"}, \code{"minkowski 0.25"},
\code{"minkowski 0.5"}, \code{"minkowski 3"}, \code{"minkowski 4"}.}

\item{\code{Clusters}}{Number of sample clusters to be created. Can be a single
integer to calculate a single cluster assignment, or a range to calculate
multiple cluster assignments.}

\item{\code{Neighbors}}{Number of nearest neighbors. Default is 20.}

\item{\code{Sigma}}{Variance for the local model. Default is 0.5.}

\item{\code{Iter}}{Number of iterations for the diffusion process. Default is 10.}

\item{\code{SpecClusterType}}{Variant of spectral clustering to use. Must be one
of: 1, 2 or 3 (default).}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_GAUDI"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_GAUDI}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_GAUDI()}}{
Multi-omics integration and sample clustering using UMAP dimensionality
reduction as described in the GAUDI method. In addition to clustering
with HDBSCAN, as done in GAUDI, we provide DBSCAN and k-means
methods for sample clustering.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_GAUDI(
  SingleOmicsUMAPNeighbors = 15,
  SingleOmicsUMAPDimensions = 4,
  SingleOmicsUMAPDistance = "euclidean",
  SingleOmicsUMAPScale = FALSE,
  SingleOmicsUMAPInit = "spectral",
  SingleOmicsUMAPPCA = NULL,
  ConcatUMAPNeighbors = 15,
  ConcatUMAPDimensions = 4,
  ConcatUMAPDistance = "euclidean",
  ConcatUMAPScale = FALSE,
  ConcatUMAPInit = "spectral",
  ConcatUMAPPCA = NULL,
  ClusterMethod = "HDBSCAN",
  HDBSCANminPts = 2,
  DBSCANeps = NULL,
  DBSCANminPts = 2,
  KmeansClusters = NULL
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{SingleOmicsUMAPNeighbors}}{Size of the local neighborhood used for
manifold approximation for each individual omics dataset. If a single
integer, all omics datasets get the same size. If a vector with the same
length as the number of omics datasets, each omics dataset gets a
different size. Default is 15, recommended range is 2-100.}

\item{\code{SingleOmicsUMAPDimensions}}{The number of dimensions into which the
individual omics datasets are embedded. If a single integer, all omics
datasets get the same number of dimensions. If a vector with the same
length as the number of omics datasets, each omics dataset gets a
different number of dimensions. Default is 4.}

\item{\code{SingleOmicsUMAPDistance}}{The distance metric used to find the
nearest neighbors in the individual omics datasets. If a single string,
all omics datasets use the same distance metric. If a vector of strings
with the same length as the number of omics datasets, each omics dataset
uses a different distance metric. Must be one of: \code{"euclidean"}
(default), \code{"cosine"}, \code{"manhattan"}, \code{"hamming"}, \code{"correlation"} or
\code{"categorical"}.}

\item{\code{SingleOmicsUMAPScale}}{Whether to perform scaling on the features of
the individual omics datasets. If a single boolean, all omics datasets
use the same scaling setting. If a vector of booleans, each omics dataset
uses a different scaling setting. Default is \code{FALSE}.}

\item{\code{SingleOmicsUMAPInit}}{Type of initialization for the coordinates of
the individual omics datasets. If a single string, all omics datasets use
the same initialization type. If a vector of strings, each omics dataset
uses a different initialization type. Must be one of: \code{"spectral"}
(default), \code{"normlaplacian"}, \code{"random"}, \code{"lvrandom"}, \code{"laplacian"},
\code{"pca"}, \code{"spca"} or \code{"agspectral"}.}

\item{\code{SingleOmicsUMAPPCA}}{Whether to reduce the number of features in the
individual omics datasets using PCA to increase the performance. May come
at a cost to accuracy. A positive integer less than the number of
features in the omics dataste is required. If a single integer, all omics
datasets are reduced to the same number of principle components. If a
vector of integers, each omics dataset is reduced to a different number
of principle components. Default is \code{NULL}.}

\item{\code{ConcatUMAPNeighbors}}{Size of the local neighborhood used for
manifold approximation for the UMAP calculation of the concatenated
single omics UMAP embeddings. Default is 15, recommended range is 2-100.}

\item{\code{ConcatUMAPDimensions}}{The number of dimensions into which the
concatenated single omics UMAP embeddings are embedded. Default is 4.}

\item{\code{ConcatUMAPDistance}}{The distance metric used to find the nearest
neighbors for the concatenated single omics UMAP embeddings. Must be one
of: \code{"euclidean"} (default), \code{"cosine"}, \code{"manhattan"}, \code{"hamming"},
\code{"correlation"} or \code{"categorical"}.}

\item{\code{ConcatUMAPScale}}{Whether to perform scaling on the UMAP dimensions
of the concatenated single omics UMAP embeddings. Default is \code{FALSE}.}

\item{\code{ConcatUMAPInit}}{Type of initialization for the coordinates of the
concatenated single omics UMAP embeddings. Must be one of: \code{"spectral"}
(default), \code{"nornlaplacian"}, \code{"random"}, \code{"lvrandom"}, \code{"laplacian"},
\code{"pca"}, \code{"spca"} or \code{"agspectral"}.}

\item{\code{ConcatUMAPPCA}}{Whether to reduce the number of UMAP dimensions of
the concatenated single omics UMAP embeddings using PCA to increase the
performance. May come at a cost to accuracy. Requires a positive integer
less than the the total number of UMAP dimension in all single omics UMAP
embeddings. Default is \code{NULL}.}

\item{\code{ClusterMethod}}{Method used for clustering of the concatenated UMAP
embedding. Must be one of: \code{"HDBSCAN"}, \code{"DBSCAN"} or \code{"Kmeans"}.}

\item{\code{HDBSCANminPts}}{Integer of the minimal size of the clusters. Default
is 2. Only included if \code{ClusterMethod} = \code{"HDBSCAN"}.}

\item{\code{DBSCANeps}}{Radius of the epsilon neighborhood. Default is \code{NULL}.
Only included if \code{ClusterMethod} = \code{"DBSCAN"}.}

\item{\code{DBSCANminPts}}{Integer of the minimal size of the clusters. Default
is 2. Only included if \code{ClusterMethod} = \code{"DBSCAN"}.}

\item{\code{KmeansClusters}}{Number of sample clusters to be created. Can be a
single integer to calculate a single cluster assignment, or a range to
calculate multiple cluster assignments. Only included if \code{ClusterMethod}
= \code{"Kmeans"}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Multi_Omics_Feature_HClust"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Multi_Omics_Feature_HClust}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_Multi_Omics_Feature_HClust()}}{
Hierarchical clustering for the feature weights calculated by the
multi-omics integration methods MoCluster, MCIA, jNMF, iNMF and MOFA.
Integrated omics feature datasets from $Multi_Omics$FeatureRes are
scaled and concatenated, and distance matrices are calculated per
multi-omics integration method. Hierarchical clustering is then
performed to cluster features from different omics types.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_Multi_Omics_Feature_HClust(
  nFactors = NULL,
  Distance = "euclidean",
  MinkowskiPower = NULL,
  Linkage = "ward.D2"
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{nFactors}}{Number of factors (components) for which the feature
hierarchical clustering is to be performed. The multi-omics integration
methods need to be performed with this number of components (MoCluster
and MCIA), clusters (jNMF and iNMF) or factors (MOFA).}

\item{\code{Distance}}{Distance metric to be used for the calculation of the
feature distance matrices. Must be one of: \code{"euclidean"} (default),
\code{"maximum"}, \code{"manhattan"}, \code{"canberra"}, \code{"binary"} or \code{"minkowski"}.
If \code{"minkowski"} is selected, argument \code{"MinkowskiPower"} needs to be
included.}

\item{\code{MinkowskiPower}}{Power of the Minkowski distance. Default is NULL.}

\item{\code{Linkage}}{Agglomeration method to be used for the hierarchical
clustering. Must be one of: \code{"ward.D"}, \code{"ward.D2"} (default), \code{"single"},
\code{"complete"}, \code{"average"}, \code{"mcquitty"}, \code{"median"} or \code{"centroid"}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Ensemble_Sample_MDS"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Ensemble_Sample_MDS}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_Ensemble_Sample_MDS()}}{
Create an ensemble clustering result by combining the clustering
results from MoCluster, MCIA, jNMF, iNMF, LRAcluster, COCA, MOFA,
SNF and GAUDI. Borrows the idea of consensus cluster, by creating a
sample similarity matrix counting the number of times samples cluster
together. Hierarchical clustering is then performed on this matrix.
Provides a more robust clustering result when performed with
multiple cluster assignment, which can be achieved by running the
multi-omics integration methods with a range of \code{Clusters}.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_Ensemble_Sample_MDS(
  Clusters = NULL,
  SNFDistance = "euclidean squared",
  Distance = "euclidean",
  MinkowskiPower = NULL,
  Linkage = "ward.D2"
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{Clusters}}{Number of clusters to create from the hierarchical
clustering result.}

\item{\code{SNFDistance}}{Which distance used to calculate SNF results to be
included in the ensemble clustering. This is needed to reduce the impact
of SNF on the ensemble clustering assignment. Must be one of:
\code{"euclidean squared"} (default), \code{"euclidean"}, \code{"manhattan"},
\code{"minkowksi 0.25"}, \code{"minkowski 0.5"}, \code{"minkowski 3"} or \code{"minkowski 4"}.}

\item{\code{Distance}}{Distance Distance metric to be used for the calculation of the
feature distance matrices. Must be one of: \code{"euclidean"} (default),
\code{"maximum"}, \code{"manhattan"}, \code{"canberra"}, \code{"binary"} or \code{"minkowski"}.
If \code{"minkowski"} is selected, argument \code{"MinkowskiPower"} needs to be
included.}

\item{\code{MinkowskiPower}}{Power of the Minkowski distance. Default is NULL.}

\item{\code{Linkage}}{Agglomeration method to be used for the hierarchical
clustering. Must be one of: \code{"ward.D"}, \code{"ward.D2"}, \code{"single"},
\code{"complete"} (default), \code{"average"}, \code{"mcquitty"}, \code{"median"} or
\code{"centroid"}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Ensemble_Sample_CCA"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Ensemble_Sample_CCA}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_Ensemble_Sample_CCA()}}{
Create an ensemble clustering result by aligning the embeddings results
from MoCluster, MCIA, jNMF, iNMF, LRAcluster, COCA, MOFA, SNF and GAUDI.
Uses CCA to align the embeddings from the multi-omics integration methods
into a common latend space. For COCA and SNF, low-dimensional embeddings
of samples are not provided, and one-hot encoding is used in place of
embedding. One method is selected as reference embedding, with all other
embeddings sequentially aligned to this reference using pairwise CCA. The
aligned embedding is then used for k-means clustering.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_Ensemble_Sample_CCA(
  Clusters = NULL,
  SNFDistance = "euclidean squared",
  Reference = "MoCluster",
  Factors = NULL,
  GAUDIMethod = "Kmeans"
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{Clusters}}{Number of clusters to create from the CCA aligned
embedding.}

\item{\code{SNFDistance}}{Which distance used to calculate SNF results to be
included in the ensemble clustering. This is needed to reduce the impact
of SNF on the ensemble clustering assignment. Must be one of:
\code{"euclidean squared"} (default), \code{"euclidean"}, \code{"manhattan"},
\code{"minkowksi 0.25"}, \code{"minkowski 0.5"}, \code{"minkowski 3"} or \code{"minkowski 4"}.}

\item{\code{Reference}}{Multi-omics integration embedding to be used as
reference for CCA alignment.}

\item{\code{Factors}}{Number of factors for which the multi-omics integration
embedding is to be selected.}

\item{\code{GAUDIMethod}}{Which clustering method is used to calculate GAUDI
results to be included in the ensemble clustering. This is needed to
reduce the impact of GAUDI on the ensemble clustering assignment. Must be
one of: \code{"Kmeans"} (default), \code{"HDBSCAN"} or \code{"DBSCAN"}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Ensemble_Integration_Feature"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Ensemble_Integration_Feature}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_Ensemble_Integration_Feature()}}{
Create an ensemble feature clustering result by combining the feature
weight results from MoCluster, MCIA, jNMF, iNMF and MOFA. Feature
weigths must be calculated for one number of components (MoCluster
and MICA), clusters (jNMF and iNMF) and factors (MOFA) to be included.
Two methods of combining the feature weights are available:
\code{"Average"} and \code{"Concatenation"}. More details of the methods are
available in the \code{param} \code{Method}.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_Ensemble_Integration_Feature(
  Method = "Average",
  nFactors = NULL,
  Distance = "euclidean",
  MinkowskiPower = NULL,
  Linkage = "ward.D2"
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{Method}}{Method used for combining the feature weight matrices of
the different multi-omics integration methods. Must be one of:
\itemize{
\item \code{"Average"}: Feature weight matrices of the different omics types
are combined per multi-omics integration method. Feature distances are
calculated per method. The average feature distance between the five
methods is calculated. Hierachical clustering is performed on the
average feature distance matrix. Default method.
\item \code{"Concatenation"}: Feature weight matrices of the different omics
types are combined per multi-omics intergration method, which are then
concatenated into a large matrix. A feature distance matrix as well as
a factor distance matrix is calculated. Hierarchical clustering is
then performed for both the features and the factors per method.
}}

\item{\code{nFactors}}{Number of factors (components) for which the feature
hierarchical clustering is to be performed. The multi-omics integration
methods need to be performed with this number of components (MoCluster
and MCIA), clusters (jNMF and iNMF) or factors (MOFA).}

\item{\code{Distance}}{Distance Distance metric to be used for the calculation of the
feature distance matrices. Must be one of: \code{"euclidean"} (default),
\code{"maximum"}, \code{"manhattan"}, \code{"canberra"}, \code{"binary"} or \code{"minkowski"}.
If \code{"minkowski"} is selected, argument \code{"MinkowskiPower"} needs to be
included.}

\item{\code{MinkowskiPower}}{Power of the Minkowski distance. Default is NULL.}

\item{\code{Linkage}}{Agglomeration method to be used for the hierarchical
clustering. Must be one of: \code{"ward.D"}, \code{"ward.D2"}, \code{"single"},
\code{"complete"} (default), \code{"average"}, \code{"mcquitty"}, \code{"median"} or
\code{"centroid"}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Feature_Optimal_Cluster"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Feature_Optimal_Cluster}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_Feature_Optimal_Cluster()}}{
Calculate the optimal number of feature clusters using the feature
hierarchical clustering tree calculated in
\code{run_Feature_Ensemble_HClust}. Will calculate the optimal number of
feature clusters for both \code{"Average"} and \code{"Concatenation"} methods
at the same time. Uses the as.clustrange function from the
WeightedCluster package to calculate the optimal number of clusters.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_Feature_Optimal_Cluster(
  WeightedClusterStat = "all",
  MaxClusters = 20
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{WeightedClusterStat}}{The statistics included to calculate the
optimal cluster number. Must be one of: \code{"all"} (default), \code{"noCH"} (all
statistics except \code{"CH"} and \code{"CHsq"}), \code{"PBC"}, \code{"HG"}, \code{"HGSD"},
\code{"ASW"}, \code{"ASWw"}, \code{"CH"}, \code{"R2"}, \code{"CHsq"}, \code{"R2sq"} or \code{"HC"}.}

\item{\code{MaxClusters}}{The maximum number of feature clusters to be
considered by the statistics. Default is 20.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Factor_Optimal_Cluster"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Factor_Optimal_Cluster}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_Factor_Optimal_Cluster()}}{
Calculate the optimal number of factor clusters using the factor
hierarchical clustering tree calculated in
\code{run_Feature_Ensemble_HClust} with \code{Method} \code{"Concatenation"}. Uses the
as.clustrange function from the WeightedCluster package to calculate the
optimal number of clusters.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_Factor_Optimal_Cluster(
  WeightedClusterStat = "all",
  MaxClusters = 10
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{WeightedClusterStat}}{The statistics included to calculate the
optimal cluster number. Must be one of: \code{"all"} (default), \code{"noCH"} (all
statistics except \code{"CH"} and \code{"CHsq"}), \code{"PBC"}, \code{"HG"}, \code{"HGSD"},
\code{"ASW"}, \code{"ASWw"}, \code{"CH"}, \code{"R2"}, \code{"CHsq"}, \code{"R2sq"} or \code{"HC"}.}

\item{\code{MaxClusters}}{The maximum number of factor clusters to be
considered by the statistics. Default is 10.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
\if{html}{\out{<hr>}}
\if{html}{\out{<a id="method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Feature_Clustering"></a>}}
\if{latex}{\out{\hypertarget{method-Ensemble_Integration_Suite-run_Feature_Clustering}{}}}
\subsection{Method \code{run_Feature_Clustering()}}{
Cut the feature hierarchical clustering tree to create feature
clusters. Can be done either using the calculated optimal feature
cluster numbers, or with user argument.
\subsection{Usage}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="r">}}\preformatted{Ensemble_Integration_Suite$run_Feature_Clustering(
  Clusters = NULL,
  Method = NULL
)}\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}

\subsection{Arguments}{
\if{html}{\out{<div class="arguments">}}
\describe{
\item{\code{Clusters}}{Number of clusters in which to cut the feature
hierarchical clustering tree. Default is \code{NULL.} If \code{NULL}, the
optimal feature cluster numbers calculated with
\code{run_Feature_Optimal_Cluster} are used, and hierarchical clustering trees
for all available \code{run_Feature_Ensemble_HClust} \code{Method} results. If an
integer, the \code{run_Feature_Ensemble_HClust} \code{Method} whose hierarchical
clustering tree is to be cut must be provided in parameter \code{Method}.}

\item{\code{Method}}{Which hierarchical clustering tree must be cut. Only
required if \code{Clusters} is an integer. Must be one of: \code{"Average"} or
\code{"Concatenation"}.}
}
\if{html}{\out{</div>}}
}
}
